This Java code defines a singly linked list with 10 nodes containing values 10 through 100, then searches for a specific value (110) in the list using a Find class with a findNode method. The findNode method traverses the list from the head, comparing each node's data with the target value; if found, it returns true, otherwise it continues until the end and returns false. Since 110 is not present in the list, the output is false.

Time Complexity: O(n) — traverses all 10 nodes in the worst case.
Space Complexity: O(1) — only uses a temporary reference variable.

import java.util.*;

class Node {
    int data;
    Node next;

    public Node(int data, Node next) {
        this.data = data;
        this.next = next;
    }

    public Node(int data) {
        this.data = data;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

class Find {
    public boolean findNode(Node head, int val){
        Node temp = head;
        while(temp!=null){
            if(temp.data == val){
                return true;
            }
            temp = temp.next;
        }
        return false;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Node head = new Node(10);
        head.next = new Node(20);
        head.next.next = new Node(30);
        head.next.next.next = new Node(40);
        head.next.next.next.next = new Node(50);
        head.next.next.next.next.next = new Node(60);
        head.next.next.next.next.next.next = new Node(70);
        head.next.next.next.next.next.next.next = new Node(80);
        head.next.next.next.next.next.next.next.next = new Node(90);
        head.next.next.next.next.next.next.next.next.next = new Node(100);
        
        Find f = new Find();
        System.out.println(f.findNode(head, 110));
        
    }
}
